The series limit of the Lyman series corresponds to a transition from the continuum \((n\rightarrow\infty)\) to the ground state \((n=1)\).  
Using the Rydberg formula  

\[
\frac{1}{\lambda}=R_{\mathrm H}\!\left(\frac{1}{1^{2}}-\frac{1}{\infty^{2}}\right)=R_{\mathrm H},
\qquad R_{\mathrm H}=1.0973731568\times10^{7}\;\text{m}^{-1},
\]

the wavelength is  

\[
\lambda=\frac{1}{R_{\mathrm H}}
        =\frac{1}{1.0973731568\times10^{7}}\;\text{m}
        =9.1127\times10^{-8}\;\text{m}
        =\boxed{91.13}\,\text{nm}.
\]

The photon energy follows from \(E = hc/\lambda\):

\[
E=\frac{(6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s})(2.99792458\times10^{8}\,\text{m·s}^{-1})}
        {9.1127\times10^{-8}\,\text{m}}
  =2.1799\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
  =\frac{2.1799\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}}{1.602176634\times10^{-19}\,\text{J/eV}}
  =\boxed{13.61}\,\text{eV}.
\]

The energy of one photon at \,λ = 1.06 µm is  

