### Inhibition of precipitation after mixing

**Initial concentrations after mixing (total volume \(V=0.20\ \text{dm}^{3}\)):**

\[
[\ce{Mg^{2+}}]_0 =\frac{0.10\ \text{dm}^{3}\times0.10\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}}{0.20\ \text{dm}^{3}}
                 =0.05\ \text{M}
\]

\[
[\ce{NH_3}]_0 =0.05\ \text{M}
\]

Let \(x\) be the added concentration of \(\ce{NH_4^{+}}\) (from solid \(\ce{NH_4Cl}\)).  
At equilibrium let \(y\) be the amount that reacts:

\[
\begin{aligned}
[\ce{NH_3}]   &=0.05-y\\
[\ce{NH_4^{+}}]&=x+y\\
[\ce{OH^-}]  &=y
\end{aligned}
\]

The base dissociation constant of ammonia is  

\[
K_b =\frac{[\ce{NH_4^{+}}][\ce{OH^-}]}{[\ce{NH_3}]}
     =\frac{(x+y)y}{0.05-y}=1.8\times10^{-5}
\]

Because precipitation must be avoided, the ion product must satisfy  

\[
[\ce{Mg^{2+}}][\ce{OH^-}]^{2}\le K_{sp}
\]

With \([\ce{Mg^{2+}}]=0.05\ \text{M}\) and \(K_{sp}=5.6\times10^{-12}\),

\[
0.05\,y^{2}\le 5.6\times10^{-12}\Longrightarrow
y\le\sqrt{\frac{5.6\times10^{-12}}{0.05}}
   =1.06\times10^{-5}\ \text{M}
\]

Because \(y\ll0.05\), we may set \(0.05-y\approx0.05\) and \(x+y\approx x\).  
Then  

\[
K_b\approx\frac{x\,y}{0.05}\Longrightarrow
y\approx\frac{K_b\cdot0.05}{x}
      =\frac{1.8\times10^{-5}\times0.05}{x}
      =\frac{9.0\times10^{-7}}{x}
\]

To keep \(y\le1.06\times10^{-5}\),

\[
\frac{9.0\times10^{-7}}{x}\le1.06\times10^{-5}
\Longrightarrow x\ge\frac{9.0\times10^{-7}}{1.06\times10^{-5}}
\approx0.085\ \text{M}
\]

Thus the final solution must contain at least \(0.085\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}\) of \(\ce{NH_4^{+}}\).

**Moles of \(\ce{NH_4Cl}\) required**

\[
n = xV = 0.085\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}\times0.20\ \text{dm}^{3}=0.017\ \text{mol}
\]

Molar mass of \(\ce{NH_4Cl}\):  

\[
