The salts NaA and NaB furnish the conjugate bases  

\[
\mathrm{A^-}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{B^-}
\]

which hydrolyse in water:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{A^-}+ \mathrm{H_2O}&\rightleftharpoons \mathrm{HA}+ \mathrm{OH^-}\qquad K_{b1}= \frac{K_w}{K_{HA}}\\[4pt]
\mathrm{B^-}+ \mathrm{H_2O}&\rightleftharpoons \mathrm{HB}+ \mathrm{OH^-}\qquad K_{b2}= \frac{K_w}{K_{HB}}
\end{aligned}
\]

with \(K_w = 1.0\times10^{-14}\).

\[
\begin{aligned}
K_{b1}&=\frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{1.74\times10^{-7}}
      =5.75\times10^{-8}\\[4pt]
K_{b2}&=\frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{1.34\times10^{-7}}
      =7.46\times10^{-8}
\end{aligned}
\]

Let the initial concentrations be  

\[
C_{A^-}=0.0600\;\text{M},\qquad C_{B^-}=0.0400\;\text{M}
\]

and denote the equilibrium hydroxide concentration by \(w=[\mathrm{OH^-}]\).

For each base, because the degree of hydrolysis is very small \((w\gg K_{b})\),

\[
[\mathrm{HA}] = \frac{K_{b1}C_{A^-}}{w},\qquad 
[\mathrm{HB}] = \frac{K_{b2}C_{B^-}}{w}
\]

and the total hydroxide is the sum of the contributions:

\[
w = \frac{K_{b1}C_{A^-}}{w}+\frac{K_{b2}C_{B^-}}{w}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
w^{2}=K_{b1}C_{A^-}+K_{b2}C_{B^-}
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
w^{2}&=(5.75\times10^{-8})(0.0600)+(7.46\times10^{-8})(0.0400)\\
     &=3.45\times10^{-9}+2.99\times10^{-9}=6.43\times10^{-9}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
w = \sqrt{6.43\times10^{-9}} = 8.0\times10^{-5}\;\text{M}
\]

Hence  

\[
p\mathrm{OH}= -\log_{10}(8.0\times10^{-5}) = 4.10
\]

\[
p\mathrm{H}=14-p\mathrm{OH}= 14-4.10 = 9.90
\]

\[
\boxed{9.90}
\]

The overall reaction for the discharge (Li⁺ from the cathode inserts into the graphite anode) can be written by combining the half‑reactions:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{Cathode:}&\quad \mathrm{CoO_2}+ \mathrm{Li^{+}}+e^- \rightarrow \mathrm{LiCoO_2}\\
\text{Anode (charging direction):}&\quad 6\,\mathrm{C}+ \mathrm{Li^{+}}+e^- \rightarrow \mathrm{LiC_6}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus, for each mole of \(\mathrm{LiCoO_2}\) formed, one mole of Li⁺ is inserted into 6 mol of carbon to give 1 mol of \(\mathrm{LiC_6}\).

---

### 1. Moles of the starting materials  

\[
\begin{aligned}
M_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} &= 6.941 + 58.933 + 2(15.999)=97.872\;\text{g mol}^{-1} \\
n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} &= \frac{10.00\;\text{g}}{97.872\;\text{g mol}^{-1}} = 0.1022\;\text{mol}
\\[4pt]
M_{\mathrm{C}} &= 12.011\;\text{g mol}^{-1} \\
n_{\mathrm{C}} &= \frac{10.00\;\text{g}}{12.011\;\text{g mol}^{-1}} = 0.8326\;\text{mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

### 2. Limiting reagent  

Each mole of \(\mathrm{LiCoO_2}\) requires 6 mol of C:

\[
n_{\mathrm{C,\,required}} = 6\,n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} = 6(0.1022)=0.613\;\text{mol}
\]

Since \(n_{\mathrm{C}} = 0.8326\;\text{mol} > 0.613\;\text{mol}\), \(\mathrm{LiCoO_2}\) is the limiting reagent.

### 3. Amount of \(\mathrm{LiC_6}\) formed  

\[
n_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} = n_{\mathrm{LiCoO_2}} = 0.1022\;\text{mol}
\]

Molar mass of \(\mathrm{LiC_6}\):

\[
M_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} = 6.941 + 6(12.011)=79.007\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
m_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} = n_{\mathrm{LiC_6}}\,M_{\mathrm{LiC_6}}
                = 0.1022 \times 79.007 = 8.07\;\text{g}
\]

### 4. Remaining graphite  

Mass of carbon consumed:

\[
m_{\mathrm{C,\,consumed}} = n_{\mathrm{C,\,required}}\,M_{\mathrm{C}}
                         = 0.613 \times 12.011 = 7.36\;\text{g}
\]

\[
m_{\mathrm{C,\,remaining}} = 10.00\;\text{g} - 7.36\;\text{g}=2.64\;\text{g}
\]

### 5. Total mass of the anode after complete discharge  

\[
m_{\text{anode}} = m_{\mathrm{LiC_6}} + m_{\mathrm{C,\,remaining}}
                 = 8.07\;\text{g} + 2.64\;\text{g}
                 = 10.71\;\text{g}
\]

\[
\boxed{10.71}\ \text{g}
\]

